<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Events to Commemorate Brown v. Board</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">February 16, 2004</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE210/en_US/040216deseg1.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Tampa Tribune</p>
			
			<p>Understanding a different era, with important lessons for today. </p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004112faeca0fb2b47ccbe005ac2">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
							
								<h3>Story Images</h3>
								<ul id="story_images">
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004112faeca0fb2b47ccbe005ac2&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=0">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE210/en_US/040216deseg2.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004112faeca0fb2b47ccbe005ac2&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=1">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE210/en_US/040216deseg3.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
			
			</ul><p  class="note">Click thumbnails for full-size images.</p>
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:lchapin@mail.ucf.edu">Linda Chapin, director, UCF Metropolitan Center for Regional Studies</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-882-1185</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto: sdowning@pegasus.cc.ucf.edu">Spencer Downing, UCF history professor</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0189</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.brownblackandwhite.org/">Brown, Black & White: A Community Reflects on Brown v. Board</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Orlando will be home this spring to one of the nations most comprehensive commemorations of the 50-year-old U.S. Supreme Court decision that led to the integration of public schools.</p><p>Hosted primarily by the University of Central Florida, two Orange County museums and an Orlando church, the series -- &quot;Brown, Black &amp; White: A Community Reflects on Brown v. Board&quot; -- will feature presentations by Cornel West, a Princeton University professor; the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth, a leader in the civil rights movement with the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.; and Henry Louis Gates Jr., the Harvard University professor who hosted the 2004 PBS series, &quot;America Beyond the Color Line.&quot;</p><p>Students and teachers who were among the first to attend integrated schools in Orange County in the 1970s are discussing their experiences with UCF students during classes and will participate in at least two public forums. UCF received a $35,000 grant from the Florida Humanities Council to help fund Brown v. Board events throughout the community.</p><p>The Orange County Regional History Center and WellsBuilt Museum for African American History are hosting panel discussions and other events, and the Orlando Sentinel, WMFEs television and radio stations, and the New Covenant Baptist Church of Orlando are among the projects other partners.</p><p>Linda Chapin, director of UCFs Metropolitan Center for Regional Studies, said its important to recognize the generation that fought hard for civil rights in addition to commemorating the 50th anniversary of the courts decision in a way that is meaningful to students. </p>
		
	
		
			<p>&quot;When our students can listen to someone talk about what it was like to be 17 years old and, backed with police and federal marshals, entering a school where you were the only person of color, where no one wanted you and where even teachers werent nice to you, its a lot easier to relate to this important history,&quot; Chapin said.</p><p>The Supreme Court handed down the landmark Brown v. Board of Education of Topeka decision on May 17, 1954. The decision, which stated that segregation equated to a denial of equal protection under the laws, did not immediately lead to the integration of black and white students in schools. Although that happened in the following two decades, concerns about segregation in schools still have not dissipated.</p><p>UCF began commemorating the 50th anniversary of the ruling in the fall, and activities will continue during the 2004-05 school year. All freshmen were given copies of Chief Justice Earl Warrens decision and related newspaper stories and editorials. Professors in psychology, education, political science and other departments have integrated the decision into their courses. </p>
		
	
		
			<p>The first community event of the spring Brown v. Board series features the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth, a Baptist minister who will speak at 5:30 p.m. Feb. 19 at the Orange County Regional History Center. Shuttlesworth led the Alabama Christian Movement for Human Rights challenges of segregation laws in Birmingham, Ala. In retaliation, his home was bombed on Christmas in 1956. A year later, he helped Martin Luther King Jr. form the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, which urged blacks to fight segregation nonviolently. Shuttlesworth now lives in Cincinnati, where he continues to work for civil rights.</p><p>Harvard University professor Henry Louis Gates Jr., chairman of the schools Department of African and African American Studies and director of Harvards W.E.B. DuBois Institute for Afro-American Research, will speak at the New Covenant Baptist Church of Orlando at 6:30 p.m. Feb. 26.</p><p>Cornel West, a professor of religion at Princeton and the author or editor of more than 20 books dealing with race, philosophy and religion, will speak at 7 p.m. March 4 at the UCF Student Union. West, author of the 1993 book, &quot;Race Matters,&quot; and Gates are co-authors of a 2000 book, &quot;The African American Century: How Black Americans Have Shaped Our Century.&quot;</p><p>Clarence Page, a Chicago Tribune columnist, and Eugene Patterson, editor emeritus of the St. Petersburg Times, will speak at 10 a.m. March 15 at the UCF Student Union. Orlando Sentinel reporters and editors will hold workshops for professional and high school journalists later that day.</p><p>WMFE will air programming related to Brown v. Board on its stations the week of Feb. 23-27. Go to <a href="http://www.brownblackandwhite.org">www.brownblackandwhite.org</a> for a full spring schedule.</p>
		
	
